08670nam a22010695i 9780226702605DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020006467  a97802267026057 a10.7208/97802267026052doi  a(DE-B1597)573121  a(OCoLC)1202462945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJK1021b.C5574 2020 4aJK1021 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a328.7300aCongress Overwhelmed :bThe Decline in Congressional Capacity and Prospects for Reform /ced. by Lee Drutman, Timothy M. LaPira, Kevin R. Kosar. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b51 line drawings, 43 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 Overwhelmed: An Introduction to Congress’s Capacity Problem -- tPart 1 The Foundations of Congressional Capacity -- t2 Capacity for What? Legislative Capacity Regimes in Congress and the Possibilities for Reform -- t3 The Decline in Congressional Capacity -- t4 How Congress Fell Behind the Executive Branch -- tPart 2 Knowledge and Expertise in Congress -- t5 The Congressional Capacity Survey: Who Staff Are, How They Got There, What They Do, and Where They May Go -- t6 What Do Congressional Staff Actually Know? -- t7 How Committee Staffers Clear the Runway for Legislative Action in Congress -- t8 Legislative Branch Support Agencies: What They Are, What They Do, and Their Uneasy Position in Our System of Government -- tPart 3 The Politics of Capacity in the Legislative Process -- t9 Still Muddling Along? Assessing the Hybrid Congressional Appropriations Process -- t10 Congress and the Capacity to Act: Overcoming Gridlock in the Senate’s Amendment Process -- t11 The Issue Dynamics of Congressional Capacity -- t12 Congressional Capacity and Reauthorizations -- t13 How Experienced Legislative Staff Contribute to Effective Lawmaking -- t14 Capacity in a Centralized Congress -- t15 Congressional Capacity and Bipartisanship in Congress -- tPart 4 Capacity and the Politics of Reform -- t16 Lessons from the History of Reform -- t17 Dodging Dead Cats: What Would It Take to Get Congress to Expand Capacity? -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCongress today is falling short. Fewer bills, worse oversight, and more dysfunction. But why? In a new volume of essays, the contributors investigate an underappreciated reason Congress is struggling: it doesn’t have the internal capacity to do what our constitutional system requires of it. Leading scholars chronicle the institutional decline of Congress and the decades-long neglect of its own internal investments in the knowledge and expertise necessary to perform as a first-rate legislature. Today’s legislators and congressional committees have fewer—and less expert and experienced—staff than the executive branch or K Street. This leaves them at the mercy of lobbyists and the administrative bureaucracy. The essays in Congress Overwhelmed assess Congress’s declining capacity and explore ways to upgrade it. Some provide broad historical scope. Others evaluate the current decay and investigate how Congress manages despite the obstacles. Collectively, they undertake the most comprehensive, sophisticated appraisal of congressional capacity to date, and they offer a new analytical frame for thinking about—and improving—our underperforming first branch of government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aCongress.  abudget and appropriations.  acongressional capacity.  acongressional staff.  agridlock.  alegislative procedure.  aoversight.  apartisanship.  ap